WEBVTT

00:02.169 --> 00:05.707
<i>NARRATOR". We lived in an electric world.
We relied on it for everything.</i>

00:06.423 --> 00:08.334
<i>And then the power went out.</i>

00:08.509 --> 00:11.501
<i>Everything stopped working.
We weren't prepared.</i>

00:11.678 --> 00:14.340
<i>Fear and confusion led to panic.</i>

00:14.515 --> 00:16.882
<i>The lucky ones made it out of the cities.</i>

00:17.059 --> 00:19.721
<i>The government collapsed.
Militias took over...</i>

00:19.895 --> 00:22.978
<i>...controlling the food supply
and stockpiling weapons.</i>

00:23.148 --> 00:25.856
<i>We still don't know
why the power went out.</i>

00:26.026 --> 00:29.610
<i>But we're hopeful that someone
will come and light the way.</i>

00:30.322 --> 00:31.608
WOMAN:
Previously <i>on</i> Revolution:

00:31.823 --> 00:34.611
- Back off!
TOM: I'm sorry you're mixed up in all this.

00:34.826 --> 00:38.239
- If I couldn't have your dad, I had to take you.
- You're a murderer.

00:38.413 --> 00:40.404
<i>- I'll</i> meet you in two weeks.
- You're leaving?

00:40.582 --> 00:43.199
"I went after Miles. Please don't worry.
Charlie."

00:43.377 --> 00:45.914
- Why are you following me?
NATE: Following your uncle, same as you.

00:46.088 --> 00:47.874
- Those are the orders.
- So you're militia.

00:48.048 --> 00:50.005
Wanna know the reason why I keep this?

00:50.175 --> 00:53.088
Somewhere inside are the only pictures
of my kids.

00:53.262 --> 00:56.630
First steps, their whole lives.
It's getting harder to remember their faces.

00:56.848 --> 00:57.929
Fire!

00:58.100 --> 00:59.340
[GUNFIRE]

00:59.518 --> 01:01.225
- Miles.
- How do you know him?

01:01.436 --> 01:06.101
This is Miles Matheson.
Commanding general of the Monroe Militia.

01:06.275 --> 01:08.186
Damn founding father of the republic...

01:08.360 --> 01:10.943
...sec0nd only
to Sebastian Monroe himself.

01:11.113 --> 01:12.194
Miles?

01:15.867 --> 01:17.357
[PANTING]

01:35.637 --> 01:36.968
[GRUNTS]

01:40.475 --> 01:42.057
WHITAKER:
Hand it over.

01:42.894 --> 01:44.805
I'm sorry. I was hungry.

01:44.980 --> 01:46.470
Hungry?

01:46.898 --> 01:47.933
I have to take you in.

01:48.191 --> 01:51.400
For what? A week's rations?
Know what they'll do to you for this?

01:51.820 --> 01:55.563
- Could just let me go.
- If I did, you know what they'd do to me?

01:58.785 --> 02:01.072
- Nice work.
- Thanks.

02:03.790 --> 02:06.031
My name is Miles Matheson.

02:08.127 --> 02:10.539
- You're joking.
- No.

02:11.006 --> 02:13.122
All the stories are true, by the way.

02:13.675 --> 02:17.088
So when I ask a question, you answer.
Okay?

02:17.429 --> 02:20.717
Captain Tom Neville.
You know him?

02:20.932 --> 02:23.424
Dark skin.
Eyes that kind of look right through you?

02:23.602 --> 02:28.096
He'd have been passing through this way
and you got the only way station for miles.

02:28.565 --> 02:29.805
[SIGHS]

02:29.983 --> 02:32.771
- He was here, all right.
- He have a prisoner with him?

02:33.362 --> 02:35.148
A boy. Nineteen, maybe. Blond hair.

02:35.530 --> 02:36.736
MILES:
Where was he going?

02:37.574 --> 02:38.609
Noblesville.

02:39.117 --> 02:40.482
And you saw him when?

02:41.286 --> 02:42.447
Yesterday.

02:43.455 --> 02:44.570
Yesterday?

02:47.125 --> 02:48.456
[GRUNTS]

02:50.629 --> 02:53.621
That wasn't so hard, was it?
Okay.

02:55.384 --> 02:56.499
Let's go.

03:01.973 --> 03:03.839
What stories does that guy know
about you?

03:04.017 --> 03:06.258
He looked like
he was about to wet himself.

03:06.645 --> 03:08.932
Come on, I told you,
it's none of your business.

03:09.106 --> 03:10.562
Look, normally, I'd agree.

03:10.732 --> 03:13.941
Except every person we meet
wants to capture you, kill you...

03:14.111 --> 03:16.648
...kill us for knowing you,
or they're terrified of you.

03:16.863 --> 03:19.400
- Charlie--
- We're so close to catching up to Danny...

03:19.574 --> 03:22.783
...and I don't know who I'm walking with
or what I'm walking into.

03:22.994 --> 03:24.405
Damn it, Charlie, shut up!

03:25.163 --> 03:28.997
Let it go. I don't owe you an explanation.
I owe you nothing.

03:29.251 --> 03:32.334
All right? You want your brother back?
Drop it.

03:32.629 --> 03:36.748
Or I swear to you, I'm out of here,
and you can find him yourself.

03:44.474 --> 03:46.340
AARON:
Don't worry. They'll come.

03:46.810 --> 03:49.518
Miles said two weeks.
Yesterday was exactly two weeks.

03:49.688 --> 03:51.599
- They're late.
- Yeah, well...

03:51.982 --> 03:55.191
...Charlie is a tough kid. She will be fine.
And they will be here.

03:59.489 --> 04:02.026
<i>ELLIOT:
Mommy? When are you coming home?</i>

04:02.784 --> 04:04.570
Two sleeps.

04:04.953 --> 04:08.287
Speaking of, it's late.
What are you guys doing up?

04:08.457 --> 04:11.119
<i>Sorry, Ms. Foster.
They refused to go to sleep until we called.</i>

04:11.293 --> 04:14.206
It's okay, Sonia.
I hope they're not burning down the house.

04:14.379 --> 04:15.961
SONIA:
No, ma'am. They're dears.

04:16.130 --> 04:18.213
<i>Read us some of</i> Wizard <i>of</i> Oz <i>first.</i>

04:18.382 --> 04:23.878
No, not tonight. I've got to go
and you've got to go to sleep.

04:24.055 --> 04:26.592
<i>Please, Mommy. Just one chapter.</i>

04:26.767 --> 04:28.804
- I <i>said no.
- Please.</i>

04:36.193 --> 04:38.150
Elliot?

04:48.538 --> 04:50.199
<i>AARON:
Maggie?</i>

04:51.208 --> 04:52.243
Maggie.

04:52.626 --> 04:55.493
Sorry, what?

04:56.505 --> 04:59.543
You know-- We can't tell them, right?

05:00.550 --> 05:02.382
Tell them about...?

05:02.928 --> 05:04.714
The, uh, pendant.

05:05.806 --> 05:08.343
What do you-- You don't trust them?

05:08.892 --> 05:10.633
You don't trust Charlie?

05:10.811 --> 05:14.224
No-- That's not my point.
Look, a thing like that...

05:14.397 --> 05:16.638
...people will kill for it. Ben died for it.

05:16.817 --> 05:20.435
- The fewer people know about it, the better.
CHARLIE: Hello?

05:20.987 --> 05:23.024
Charlie?

05:39.256 --> 05:40.917
Wasn't sure I'd see you again, heh.

05:41.258 --> 05:44.671
I'm fine. A few tight scrapes, but...

05:44.845 --> 05:48.509
- How are you guys?
- Fine. Fine. We're just happy to see you.

05:49.432 --> 05:51.218
This is Nora.

05:51.768 --> 05:54.851
And this is who's going up
against the militia? Really?

05:55.021 --> 05:57.729
- Now you see what I mean?
- Um, we're standing right here.

05:57.899 --> 06:01.187
And this is all charming, but come on.
Grab your crap. Let's go.

06:01.361 --> 06:03.147
- Oh, now?
- Yeah.

06:03.613 --> 06:06.651
Yeah, Danny's close.
We can maybe catch up by tomorrow.

06:06.825 --> 06:08.315
- You're joking.
- No.

06:08.493 --> 06:10.484
MAGGIE:
Let's hurry, then.

06:30.473 --> 06:33.181
[GRUNTING AND CHEWING]

06:34.269 --> 06:35.634
What is that?

06:56.124 --> 06:57.364
[GRUNTING]

07:02.047 --> 07:03.253
[BARKING]

07:10.472 --> 07:11.928
Run!

07:21.816 --> 07:23.306
[DOGS BARKING]

07:39.960 --> 07:40.995
[AARON YELLS]

07:41.169 --> 07:43.001
MAGGIE:
Aaron!

07:44.381 --> 07:45.871
[DOG WHIMPERS]

07:47.801 --> 07:49.633
My I69-

07:49.803 --> 07:51.293
[PANTING]

07:53.264 --> 07:54.754
[THUNDER RUMBLING]

08:04.609 --> 08:06.145
DANNY:
Hey.

08:06.820 --> 08:08.811
- Captain.
- What?

08:09.739 --> 08:12.948
- Hold them up.
MAN: Hold them up.

08:13.785 --> 08:17.153
- A storm's coming.
- You scared of a little thunder?

08:19.541 --> 08:21.327
You didn't feel the shift in the air?

08:24.462 --> 08:27.500
I am telling you
that we should find shelter.

08:28.758 --> 08:31.876
JIMMY: Sir.
- The boy says we need to stop.

08:32.971 --> 08:34.803
Says we have some weather coming.

08:34.972 --> 08:37.681
Sir, we keep going,
we'll be in Noblesville by dawn.

08:37.851 --> 08:39.842
It's only an hour away.

08:56.661 --> 08:58.527
Good evening, Rachel.

08:58.830 --> 08:59.991
Can't sleep?

09:00.790 --> 09:03.999
I never do sleep very well here, I'm...

09:04.669 --> 09:06.034
I'm not sure why.

09:06.838 --> 09:08.328
What do you want, Bass?

09:10.383 --> 09:11.919
What do I want?

09:13.803 --> 09:16.386
Rachel, as if you don't know.

09:17.015 --> 09:19.677
As if you don't know
what I've always wanted.

09:21.686 --> 09:23.677
Do we really have to play this game?

09:31.738 --> 09:34.070
You've asked me these questions
a hundred times.

09:34.365 --> 09:36.697
And I'm gonna ask you again.

09:38.369 --> 09:40.451
What was Ben working on?

09:41.372 --> 09:43.363
Ben was an algebra teacher.

09:43.875 --> 09:45.365
[CHUCKLES]

09:47.712 --> 09:50.044
If Ben was an algebra teacher...

09:51.091 --> 09:53.628
...why was he working
for the Department of Defense?

09:54.636 --> 09:57.219
And why did he have full SAP clearance?

09:58.473 --> 10:02.216
Why, on the night of the blackout,
did he call Miles...

10:03.228 --> 10:06.562
...and tell him the power was going out
five seconds before it did?

10:09.567 --> 10:12.400
If Ben knew why the lights went out...

10:14.364 --> 10:16.275
...he'd know how to turn them back on.

10:17.867 --> 10:20.108
I don't know what you're talking about.

10:23.123 --> 10:25.581
Haven't I been a good host to you,
Rachel?

10:25.750 --> 10:27.411
[SCOFFS]

10:30.463 --> 10:31.999
I mean...

10:32.257 --> 10:35.500
...I haven't put you in a dungeon.

10:36.886 --> 10:38.126
I haven't killed you.

10:40.932 --> 10:43.765
That's out of respect to you.

10:44.602 --> 10:46.263
To our friendship.

10:52.777 --> 10:53.938
Sergeant Strausser.

11:12.797 --> 11:17.007
Mrs. Matheson. My apologies.

11:18.136 --> 11:19.297
In advance.

11:22.724 --> 11:24.260
[AARON GROANING]

11:25.018 --> 11:26.725
Think I got rabies?

11:27.145 --> 11:28.510
Probably not.

11:28.855 --> 11:33.019
Probably not. Oh, this is great.
This is so great.

11:35.361 --> 11:36.522
Ohh.

11:58.009 --> 12:02.253
You know, Charlie didn't deserve that.
You exploding at her today.

12:03.097 --> 12:04.713
I know.

12:06.517 --> 12:08.178
You should go easier on her.

12:08.770 --> 12:12.013
I'm gonna go a whole lot easier on her.
I'm gonna--

12:13.191 --> 12:14.602
I'm gonna leave.

12:15.902 --> 12:17.859
Excuse me?

12:18.029 --> 12:21.021
It is better for everybody if I leave.

12:21.199 --> 12:23.031
Better for them? It's better for you.

12:23.201 --> 12:25.112
Got the entire militia gunning for me.

12:25.370 --> 12:28.533
You're the same selfish dick
with the same crap excuses...

12:28.706 --> 12:31.619
...and whenever you get close to anyone,
you take off.

12:31.793 --> 12:35.206
This is not about us.
Don't start talking like it is, okay?

12:35.380 --> 12:38.918
You're right. It's about Charlie.
And you made her a promise.

12:39.092 --> 12:41.584
I don't...
I don't need any of this.

12:41.761 --> 12:44.879
- She's your family.
- Doesn't make her my responsibility.

12:46.224 --> 12:47.806
I have no idea...

12:48.017 --> 12:51.385
...why I signed on for this in the first place.
It's not my fault...

12:51.562 --> 12:53.428
...that her dad's dead.

12:53.606 --> 12:56.314
Not my fault what happened to her mom.

12:58.903 --> 13:01.395
I don't even know Charlie.

13:03.074 --> 13:08.114
Family or not, I'm just
not doing this anymore. I'm out.

13:31.644 --> 13:33.601
Why do you have to leave?

13:38.276 --> 13:41.644
She's going for supplies.
It's important, Charlie.

13:44.824 --> 13:47.612
But you've never gone on a trip
like this before.

13:48.786 --> 13:51.118
I'll be back in a couple of months.

13:51.873 --> 13:54.535
Months? That's such a long time.

13:54.709 --> 13:56.450
- Just please don't go.
RACHEL: Hey.

13:57.795 --> 13:59.627
I need your help.

14:00.214 --> 14:01.955
You listen to your dad.

14:02.800 --> 14:05.337
Protect your brother. Promise?

14:11.809 --> 14:15.018
- I love you.
CHARLIE: I love you too.

14:26.324 --> 14:27.860
Come here.

14:33.414 --> 14:35.655
Mom. Mom, please.

14:36.167 --> 14:38.750
Mom, don't go!

14:39.712 --> 14:42.500
Mom, please. Please!

14:44.675 --> 14:46.712
Don't go.

14:51.766 --> 14:55.851
- You all right?
- Yeah, I think so, thank you.

14:56.020 --> 14:57.351
[DOGS BARKING]

14:58.523 --> 15:00.013
MILES:
Let's go.

15:20.044 --> 15:21.534
[THUNDER RUMBLING]

15:52.410 --> 15:53.900
[THUNDER RUMBLING]

15:57.457 --> 15:59.414
[HORSES NEIGHING]

16:02.253 --> 16:03.914
SOLDIER 1:
Hyah! Hyah!

16:08.634 --> 16:09.795
SOLDIER 2:
Get in there.

16:14.265 --> 16:15.596
SOLDIER 3:
Get them inside.

16:18.561 --> 16:22.930
Let's get this gear tied down, gentlemen.
Get that door secure.

16:26.819 --> 16:28.526
Put it over here. Put it over here.

16:32.325 --> 16:35.238
- Don't move.
SOLDIER 4: Easy with that.

16:48.424 --> 16:52.008
AARON: The funny thing is I used to be
a dog person. I loved them.

16:52.595 --> 16:55.758
- Had a King Charles Cavalier.
NORA: A what?

16:55.932 --> 16:58.094
AARON:
They called them the lapdog of kings.

16:58.267 --> 17:01.430
Its name was Zoey.
Sometimes it wore a sweater.

17:01.604 --> 17:02.969
NORA:
Wow.

17:05.691 --> 17:07.181
Be right back.

17:16.618 --> 17:17.905
[GRUNTING]

17:35.429 --> 17:36.590
CHARLIE:
Stop!

17:36.764 --> 17:38.175
- Stop it! Stop!
MAGGIE: Miles.

17:38.349 --> 17:40.966
- How long you been following us?
- Long enough. You just noticed?

17:41.143 --> 17:43.726
- You must be getting old.
- Oh, stop it, both of you!

17:43.896 --> 17:46.228
- He's militia.
- Nate, right?

17:46.732 --> 17:49.349
- His name's not Nate.
- How do you know?

17:50.444 --> 17:53.436
- I saw him near Pontiac.
- You what?

17:53.614 --> 17:56.527
She cuffed me to a pole.
Took me two days to get free.

17:56.701 --> 18:00.035
- Look, I thought I handled it.
- Yes, clearly you handled it.

18:00.204 --> 18:03.162
- Look, we have bigger problems here.
MILES: He's a spy, Charlie.

18:03.332 --> 18:05.323
Who knows what he told Neville.
Or Monroe.

18:05.501 --> 18:08.869
So let's find out. He's part of Neville's unit.
You said so yourself.

18:09.547 --> 18:12.881
Don't you think maybe he knows
something about Neville? Or Danny?

18:14.135 --> 18:16.627
Besides, what the hell do you care?
You're leaving.

18:20.558 --> 18:25.018
- She's got a point, Miles.
- Oh, hey. It's all good with me.

18:25.813 --> 18:28.100
I just get to keep a closer eye.

18:30.818 --> 18:31.899
Where are you going?

18:32.528 --> 18:35.771
Oh, I'm going to get my sword,
if that's okay with you.

18:36.866 --> 18:38.527
Go to hell.

18:46.125 --> 18:48.742
England? Lady, that's just not possible.

18:48.919 --> 18:52.162
No, but I spoke to a man in Montana,
and he said--

18:52.340 --> 18:54.672
You walked here? From Montana?

18:54.842 --> 18:57.083
No, I walked here from Seattle.

18:57.553 --> 19:02.093
And he said that you could
get to the Atlantic from just here.

19:02.266 --> 19:04.883
Well, you could,
but nobody does anymore.

19:05.519 --> 19:10.889
No. You don't understand how long it took,
what I've been through just to get here.

19:11.067 --> 19:14.185
Lady, trust me. You can't get to the--

19:14.362 --> 19:17.821
- But I have to get home.
- You can't get to England either.

19:17.990 --> 19:20.573
There are no more tall ships.
No more steam boats.

19:20.993 --> 19:25.157
They were destroyed in the wars, or ripped
apart for lumber, or the militia's got them.

19:27.458 --> 19:30.416
Hell, getting to England
is like trying to get to the moon.

19:36.509 --> 19:38.420
Maybe one day.

19:41.764 --> 19:43.926
You've been very kind.

19:45.101 --> 19:46.762
[THUNDER RUMBLING]

19:46.936 --> 19:48.347
[HORSES NEIGHING]

19:48.521 --> 19:51.229
NEVILLE:
Anything that moves gotta get tied down.

19:51.399 --> 19:53.891
Storm's coming, fellas.
Gotta get this stuff secure.

19:54.068 --> 19:58.062
Put it over here. Get your asses in gear.
Come on, come on, move it.

19:58.489 --> 19:59.945
Let's go. Come on.

20:00.616 --> 20:04.154
SOLDIER 1 : A horse is loose!
SOLDIER 2: Get him. Come here, boy.

20:05.079 --> 20:06.569
[GRUNTING]

20:08.124 --> 20:10.331
Easy, Easy.
Easy now. Easy now.

20:23.472 --> 20:24.633
[GRUNTING]

20:34.608 --> 20:38.772
Come on, come on! Go, go!

20:52.501 --> 20:54.788
So you're leaving, huh?

20:55.880 --> 20:57.871
It's for the best.

20:58.674 --> 21:01.757
You don't know who I am, Maggie.
You don't know what I've done.

21:02.011 --> 21:05.174
I do actually. Charlie told me.

21:06.140 --> 21:08.051
That makes you a murderer, right?

21:08.851 --> 21:10.933
Maybe one of the great ones.

21:11.562 --> 21:14.771
Then you understand why
she's better off without me.

21:15.191 --> 21:17.899
That's probably true.

21:18.068 --> 21:21.902
But what makes you think
you're better off without her?

21:22.740 --> 21:24.697
The hell is that supposed to mean?

21:29.622 --> 21:33.240
I spent years trying to get back to my boys.

21:35.878 --> 21:37.539
Years.

21:39.006 --> 21:43.546
<i>I walked across the country.
And then up and down the East Coast.</i>

21:43.928 --> 21:48.092
<i>You'd think I could find one damn ship
to take me home.</i>

21:49.016 --> 21:50.677
But I never did.

21:53.729 --> 21:55.515
Until...

21:59.652 --> 22:01.108
I gave UP-

22:01.862 --> 22:07.073
Knew I'd never see my kids again.
That they probably died.

22:07.243 --> 22:12.454
Scared. Alone. Crying for their mother.

22:14.208 --> 22:15.323
So...

22:16.669 --> 22:17.955
...I wandered.

22:18.963 --> 22:22.206
<i>Found myself in Wisconsin.
Picked a nice spot.</i>

22:22.383 --> 22:25.000
<i>Poured myself a cup of poison.</i>

22:26.220 --> 22:29.884
And then, of all people...

22:30.474 --> 22:32.590
...your brother found me.

22:37.189 --> 22:38.224
Hey.

22:40.317 --> 22:43.230
Sorry, I don't mean any harm.
I just need to fill these up.

22:45.739 --> 22:48.948
Could you do that somewhere else?

22:50.286 --> 22:53.278
I'd rather be on my own.

22:59.545 --> 23:02.708
This might be a flier, but my kids and I
have a campfire nearby.

23:02.882 --> 23:05.294
We caught more food than we can eat.

23:06.385 --> 23:07.875
Are you hungry?

23:09.305 --> 23:14.926
I think he saw something
desperate in my eyes.

23:17.479 --> 23:20.938
Yeah. That sounds like Ben.

23:22.985 --> 23:24.350
I met his kids.

23:25.863 --> 23:31.734
<i>Followed them all back home.
And then I came to love them.</i>

23:33.203 --> 23:36.412
Ben and his kids, they gave me
a reason to live.

23:36.707 --> 23:39.324
They saved my life, Miles. They...

23:40.419 --> 23:42.410
...saved me.

23:43.714 --> 23:50.677
So if you give that girl half a chance,
maybe she can do the same for you.

24:08.530 --> 24:10.771
[DOGS GROWLING AND BARKING]

24:17.289 --> 24:20.498
There's a diner right behind us.
Count of three, we haul ass, okay?

24:24.964 --> 24:26.625
Three!

24:38.227 --> 24:40.844
- Where's Maggie?
- She was right behind me.

24:41.355 --> 24:43.096
Help!

24:43.691 --> 24:44.977
Help!

24:45.150 --> 24:46.390
[GRUNTING]

24:50.906 --> 24:52.362
[GROANING]

24:52.533 --> 24:53.944
MILES:
Hey!

25:00.416 --> 25:02.953
Okay. Come on, come on, come on.

25:03.168 --> 25:05.409
Maggie. What happened?

25:05.879 --> 25:08.041
MILES: There's a guy out there.
- What guy? Who?

25:08.257 --> 25:09.418
Maggie, what did he say?

25:09.591 --> 25:12.879
He said I killed his dog.

25:16.140 --> 25:18.006
MILES: Oh, this is great.
MAGGIE: Hey, listen.

25:18.475 --> 25:21.308
It's not just a pack of strays.
They belong to that psycho.

25:21.478 --> 25:23.560
- They're his attack dogs.
MAGGIE: Listen.

25:23.981 --> 25:25.517
He severed an artery.

25:28.485 --> 25:29.941
I'm bleeding out.

25:36.118 --> 25:37.608
[THUNDER RUMBLING]

25:39.079 --> 25:41.537
So, Danny boy.

25:42.082 --> 25:44.073
How'd you get out of those cuffs?

25:45.502 --> 25:47.994
Look. We're stuck here.

25:48.172 --> 25:53.338
You can glower at me like you're
sucking on a lemon. Or we can be civil.

25:54.470 --> 25:57.963
I like you, Danny.
You remind me of my own boy.

25:58.891 --> 26:01.508
- You have a son?
- Yes, I do.

26:02.436 --> 26:04.552
Am I really such a monster?

26:07.357 --> 26:09.974
Am I really so different than your father?

26:11.528 --> 26:15.943
I just want a future for my child.

26:18.744 --> 26:21.532
Well, my dad didn't murder people.

26:22.998 --> 26:25.990
He didn't hurt people like it was nothing.

26:32.466 --> 26:35.424
You don't remember
the days after the Blackout.

26:35.844 --> 26:41.260
No food. No water. Nothing but panic
and death everywhere you turned.

26:44.520 --> 26:48.639
If your daddy could go through all that
and hold onto that kind of mercy...

26:48.857 --> 26:53.647
...then my hat is off to him.
He was a better man than I.

26:57.908 --> 27:01.196
CHARLIE: Sit back. Sit back. Okay.
MILES: All right.

27:01.411 --> 27:04.073
With those dogs out there,
how the hell do we get out?

27:04.915 --> 27:06.326
Right.

27:06.500 --> 27:08.912
Just keep the doors locked.
Nora. Let's go.

27:09.086 --> 27:11.999
- You're going out? They're outside.
MILES: We'll get on the roof.

27:12.172 --> 27:13.958
Hopscotch a few buildings over.

27:14.133 --> 27:16.170
- Put some distance between us.
- To do what?

27:17.678 --> 27:19.134
I'm gonna find this whack job.

27:20.305 --> 27:22.387
And he's gonna call off his mutts.
Believe me.

27:28.772 --> 27:30.558
How can we help?

27:30.732 --> 27:33.941
Leave. You know you have to leave, right?

27:34.111 --> 27:35.601
Maggie. No way.

27:35.821 --> 27:38.563
Danny is 24 hours from here.
You're wasting time.

27:38.740 --> 27:41.573
We'll get Danny back.
All of us. Together.

27:41.743 --> 27:45.281
MAGGIE: If you lost him because of me,
I'd never forgive myself.

27:45.455 --> 27:46.911
Charlie, please.

27:51.420 --> 27:56.039
Maggie, I know I haven't been easy.

27:56.216 --> 27:58.878
My mom was gone and then you were there
and I didn't--

27:59.052 --> 28:02.044
- It's all right. I understand.
CHARLIE: You were there.

28:02.639 --> 28:05.256
You were always there for me.

28:05.434 --> 28:08.802
Kind. Protective.

28:08.979 --> 28:10.060
Annoying-

28:10.230 --> 28:11.686
[BOTH CHUCKLE]

28:13.192 --> 28:16.605
The least I can do is give you
a taste of your own medicine.

28:17.571 --> 28:19.187
We're staying.

28:47.309 --> 28:48.595
Amen!

28:53.398 --> 28:54.729
[GROANING]

28:54.900 --> 29:00.316
Listen. The tourniquet's not good enough.
I'm losing too much blood.

29:00.489 --> 29:01.945
CHARLIE:
What do we do?

29:02.115 --> 29:07.485
There's a sewing needle in my bag.
Some clamps. They look like scissors.

29:07.913 --> 29:10.780
- Wait. What are you saying?
- You need to stitch the artery.

29:10.999 --> 29:13.616
- You're talking about us doing surgery?
- What's first?

29:13.835 --> 29:19.001
You need to sterilize everything.
I think Miles has some whiskey.

29:23.345 --> 29:24.506
[CHARLIE SCREAMS]

29:24.680 --> 29:26.591
- Charlie!
- Damn it, Charlie!

29:29.142 --> 29:30.724
Charlie.

29:31.728 --> 29:33.639
Charlie!

29:36.775 --> 29:38.265
[THUNDER RUMBLING]

29:43.615 --> 29:45.197
[DOGS BARKING IN DISTANCE]

29:45.450 --> 29:47.612
- Couldn't find him.
- Miles, he took Charlie.

29:47.786 --> 29:49.777
- He what?
- Which door did he come in?

29:49.955 --> 29:51.537
Miles. Heavily armed.

29:51.707 --> 29:55.245
Multiple knives. Hauled it through
the kitchen. Last look, she was alive.

30:00.299 --> 30:01.334
You're coming with me.

30:01.508 --> 30:02.873
AARON:
Uh.

30:03.051 --> 30:07.215
- I need to operate. I need help.
<i>- I'll</i> stay.

30:09.766 --> 30:11.222
I'll bring her back, Maggie.

30:18.608 --> 30:20.565
NEVILLE:
Hey, Danny boy.

30:20.736 --> 30:22.067
[PANTING]

30:23.405 --> 30:25.021
[WHINING]

30:25.907 --> 30:27.739
Aren't I in a pickle?

30:27.909 --> 30:30.492
I don't suppose I could get a little help
over here?

30:34.791 --> 30:37.783
You walk up those stairs,
that's just like killing me.

30:38.754 --> 30:40.961
So I'm supposed to show you mercy now?

30:41.214 --> 30:45.082
Look. I know I don't have the right.

30:48.263 --> 30:52.131
If your father was the man
you said he was...

30:52.309 --> 30:53.970
...how do you think he'd feel?

30:54.144 --> 30:57.637
To see his son
murder someone in cold blood?

31:08.825 --> 31:11.863
Tell me. What would your father do?

31:19.044 --> 31:20.876
Come on, boy.

31:21.963 --> 31:23.670
Come on, help me out.

31:49.658 --> 31:51.319
You son of a bitch.

31:51.493 --> 31:52.824
[GRUNTING]

31:53.328 --> 31:54.318
I'm sorry.

31:55.372 --> 31:56.703
But you're important, kid.

31:57.541 --> 31:59.202
More important than you even know.

32:10.220 --> 32:12.086
KINSEY:
Don't be afraid.

32:12.264 --> 32:14.005
You're home.

32:14.433 --> 32:15.514
My home.

32:17.727 --> 32:19.388
You live here?

32:19.855 --> 32:21.345
What's wrong with here?

32:21.523 --> 32:23.514
Nothing. It's--

32:23.692 --> 32:25.854
Safe. It's practical.

32:26.027 --> 32:28.860
You can survive a long time down here.

32:29.072 --> 32:32.190
Can you please...
Please, let me go?

32:32.367 --> 32:33.778
KINSEY:
Let you go?

32:33.952 --> 32:35.738
You'd kill me if you had the chance.

32:35.912 --> 32:39.030
No. No, we don't wanna hurt you,
that's not why we--

32:39.207 --> 32:40.447
No.

32:40.709 --> 32:42.700
No one wants to hurt anyone.

32:42.878 --> 32:46.963
You look hard enough,
you can find the good in everyone.

32:47.716 --> 32:49.206
That's what Lila used to say.

32:51.219 --> 32:53.961
Who's Lila? Is that your wife?

32:54.931 --> 32:57.719
No. My daughter.

32:57.893 --> 32:59.634
Is she here?

33:02.063 --> 33:03.553
She's dead.

33:05.609 --> 33:07.065
I'm sorry.

33:07.569 --> 33:10.903
It was my job to protect her.

33:12.073 --> 33:14.235
What other job does a father have?

33:14.993 --> 33:19.112
We stored up food. Meds.
Everything except a gun.

33:20.373 --> 33:22.159
That turned out to be a mistake.

33:26.421 --> 33:30.164
Looters came. I fought them off,
but there was too many.

33:30.592 --> 33:32.674
Did they kill her?

33:33.178 --> 33:35.920
Not right away, but yes.

33:36.097 --> 33:40.261
A few weeks later, Lila stepped on a nail.

33:40.477 --> 33:42.593
Simple and stupid as that.

33:42.771 --> 33:44.432
She got tetanus.

33:44.606 --> 33:46.392
She couldn't even open her mouth.

33:47.776 --> 33:53.818
She just sat there, dying of thirst
right in front of me. Nothing I could do.

33:55.116 --> 33:56.902
I could have saved her.

33:58.119 --> 34:00.486
Would have been easy, if I had the meds.

34:02.541 --> 34:04.782
If the looters hadn't taken everything.

34:05.669 --> 34:08.001
I'm so sorry. I am.

34:09.965 --> 34:12.172
But people just aren't like that anymore.

34:12.926 --> 34:15.132
They've always been like that.

34:16.054 --> 34:19.547
You know, you remind me of Lila.

34:29.650 --> 34:31.187
You know...

34:32.320 --> 34:35.654
...you could stay. If you want.

34:36.324 --> 34:38.985
We wouldn't have to be lonely.

34:46.960 --> 34:47.995
You little bitch.

34:48.670 --> 34:51.708
Acting all nice.
Just because you're scared.

34:52.674 --> 34:53.755
MILES:
Charlie!

34:55.342 --> 34:56.458
Help!

34:56.844 --> 34:58.711
Help, Miles!

35:00.265 --> 35:02.176
KINSEY:
You can't trust anyone.

35:04.853 --> 35:06.093
Charlie.

35:17.824 --> 35:19.360
[GRUNTING]

35:21.745 --> 35:23.076
Where is she?

35:37.844 --> 35:38.879
[CHARLIE MUFFLED SCREAMING]

35:39.054 --> 35:40.294
Charlie.

35:45.185 --> 35:46.220
MILES:
Charlie.

35:52.734 --> 35:55.146
[CHARLIE CONTINUES
MUFFLED SCREAMING]

35:55.737 --> 35:57.398
MILES:
Charlie, where are you?

36:03.078 --> 36:06.616
NATE: Charlie, where are you?
- Charlie!

36:10.585 --> 36:12.917
NATE:
Charlie! Charlie!

36:14.422 --> 36:15.833
Charlie.

36:16.883 --> 36:18.248
Charlie.

36:18.426 --> 36:19.916
[CHARLIE MUFFLED SCREAMING]

36:31.856 --> 36:34.473
You okay? Look at me.

36:34.984 --> 36:36.270
Are you okay?

36:38.279 --> 36:40.395
[DOGS BARKING]

36:41.324 --> 36:42.940
[DOGS CEASE BARKING]

36:44.411 --> 36:45.742
[DOOR OPENS]

36:46.496 --> 36:47.907
NORA:
What happened to the dogs?

36:48.164 --> 36:49.404
Gave them a time-out.

36:49.582 --> 36:52.449
- Charlie?
- I'm fine. How is she?

36:52.627 --> 36:54.288
AARON:
I'm, uh, almost done.

37:00.009 --> 37:02.000
You saved me, Charlie.

37:02.387 --> 37:04.253
That's right, we're gonna save you. Okay.

37:04.431 --> 37:07.640
MAGGIE:
No. You saved me.

37:08.268 --> 37:09.599
Thank you.

37:09.978 --> 37:12.640
No, no, don't talk like that.
You're gonna be okay.

37:12.814 --> 37:16.978
- I've lost too much blood.
- No. I did just what you said.

37:20.613 --> 37:22.399
I'd like my phone.

37:23.533 --> 37:25.649
Maggie, please.

37:47.432 --> 37:48.467
[CHUCKLES]

37:48.641 --> 37:51.850
"Dorothy now took Toto up
solemnly in her arms...

37:52.020 --> 37:54.227
...and having said one last goodbye...

37:54.397 --> 37:58.356
...she clapped the heels of her shoes
together three times...

37:58.526 --> 38:03.020
...saying, 'Take me home.
Take me home to Aunt Em'."

38:07.368 --> 38:11.487
Please don't go, Maggie.
Maggie, please don't go.

38:11.706 --> 38:13.538
Maggie.

38:14.000 --> 38:15.866
MAGGIE:
Bye-b ye, Dorothy.

38:16.753 --> 38:18.164
Bye-bye.

38:20.882 --> 38:24.671
<i>BYe-We- Bye-bye.</i>

38:36.397 --> 38:38.013
CHARLIE:
Please don't go, please.

38:38.191 --> 38:39.226
[CRYING]

38:39.400 --> 38:41.016
Please don't leave me.

38:41.528 --> 38:43.110
Maggie.

38:47.575 --> 38:50.784
Everybody leaves me. Please don't.

39:12.433 --> 39:14.424
I'm not going anywhere.

39:15.436 --> 39:16.926
Okay?

39:18.439 --> 39:20.646
I'm not gonna leave.

39:34.581 --> 39:36.788
Back for more questions?

39:37.834 --> 39:40.451
No, just one question, Rachel.

39:42.130 --> 39:44.212
What kind of a mother are you?

39:45.800 --> 39:47.165
Excuse me?

39:48.803 --> 39:52.717
Well, you abandoned your children.

39:53.725 --> 39:56.183
You left them alone with Ben.

39:56.352 --> 40:00.971
Did you even stop and hesitate?

40:02.692 --> 40:04.228
Did it hurt?

40:05.486 --> 40:09.150
Or are you just too cold of a bitch
to feel anything?

40:11.701 --> 40:13.738
Don't answer that.

40:15.663 --> 40:18.325
Now, your son's gonna be here
very soon.

40:19.834 --> 40:22.496
And you think you're tough.

40:23.338 --> 40:25.500
But let's see how tough you are...

40:25.673 --> 40:29.166
...when we start ripping out his molars.

40:31.262 --> 40:34.129
Let's see if you start talking then.

40:37.936 --> 40:41.349
Or like I said. Maybe...

40:43.066 --> 40:45.683
...you don't even care about your kids.

40:46.945 --> 40:49.937
I guess we'll find out soon enough,
won't we?

41:03.711 --> 41:06.169
Mom. Mom.

41:06.589 --> 41:09.798
Please. Mom, don't go.

41:10.093 --> 41:11.709
<i>MOM.!</i>

41:13.221 --> 41:15.804
Mom! Please.

41:17.183 --> 41:18.673
Please.

41:36.077 --> 41:37.317
I came.

41:41.833 --> 41:43.449
Like you asked.

41:55.972 --> 42:00.842
Miles, you promise me.
Just promise I see my kids again.

42:56.199 --> 42:58.190
[English - US - SDH]
